<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,325,892]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,470,496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Remarks.</emphasis>
Primary 
<typeStatus box="[419,467,470,496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hutton" authorityName="Hutton" authorityYear="1873" box="[604,825,470,496]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Rissoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vana">
<emphasis box="[604,739,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Rissoa vana</emphasis>
Hutton
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated here for the first time in pl. 1, fig. G. The original description of this species was based on one or more specimens collected from Awamoa Creek, Oamaru. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hutton, F. W." box="[151,324,542,568]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref61878" refString="Hutton, F. W. (1873 c) Catalogue of the Tertiary Mollusca and Echinodermata of New Zealand, in the Collection of the Colonial Museum. Colonial Museum and Geological Survey Department Natural History Publication 6. Government Printer, Wellington, 48 pp." type="book" year="1873">
<taxonomicName authority="Brook &amp; Kennedy &amp; King &amp; Ridden &amp; Shaw &amp; Spencer, 2020" authorityName="Brook &amp; Kennedy &amp; King &amp; Ridden &amp; Shaw &amp; Spencer" authorityYear="2020" box="[151,229,542,568]" genus="Hutton" pageId="14" pageNumber="65" rank="genus" status="nov. gen.">Hutton</taxonomicName>
(1873c)
</bibRefCitation>
interpreted 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hutton" authorityYear="1873" box="[461,515,543,568]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Rissoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vana">
<emphasis box="[461,515,543,568]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">vana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a marine species derived from a Miocene fossil assemblage, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Finlay, H. J." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="480 - 494" refId="ref60314" refString="Finlay, H. J. (1924) New Zealand Tertiary rissoids. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, 55, 480 - 494." type="journal article" year="1924">Finlay (1924: 491</bibRefCitation>
, 493) pointed out that it is a synonym of the extant freshwater snail 
<taxonomicName authority="Gould, 1848" authorityName="Gould" authorityYear="1848" box="[922,1240,578,604]" class="Gastropoda" family="Amnicolidae" genus="Amnicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="badia">
<emphasis box="[922,1098,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Amnicola badia</emphasis>
Gould, 1848
</taxonomicName>
[= 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray, 1843)" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Potamopyrgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="antipodarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Potamopyrgus antipodarum</emphasis>
(Gray, 1843)
</taxonomicName>
]. 
<bibRefCitation author="Finlay, H. J." box="[466,618,614,640]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="480 - 494" refId="ref60314" refString="Finlay, H. J. (1924) New Zealand Tertiary rissoids. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, 55, 480 - 494." type="journal article" year="1924">Finlay (1924)</bibRefCitation>
noted that this species was common in Awamoa Creek and suggested that the 
<typeStatus box="[192,240,650,676]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hutton" authorityYear="1873" box="[375,429,651,676]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Rissoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vana">
<emphasis box="[375,429,651,676]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">vana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was probably collected from Recent flood deposits. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1015,1329,650,676]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Potamopyrgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="antipodarum">
<emphasis box="[1015,1329,650,676]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Potamopyrgus antipodarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed throughout 
<collectingCountry box="[406,556,686,712]" name="New Zealand" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
in fresh and brackish water (
<bibRefCitation author="Winterbourn, M." box="[876,1085,686,712]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="283 - 321" refId="ref70371" refString="Winterbourn, M. (1970) The New Zealand species of Potamopyrgus (Gastropoda: Hydrobiidae). Malacologia, 10, 283 - 321." type="journal article" year="1970">Winterbourn 1970</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Haase, M." box="[1096,1287,686,712]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="99 - 159" refId="ref61246" refString="Haase, M. (2008) The radiation of hydrobiid gastropods in New Zealand: a revision including the description of new species based on morphology and mtDNA sequence information. Systematics and Biodiversity, 6 (1), 99 - 159. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / s 1477200007002630" type="journal article" year="2008">Haase 2008: 103</bibRefCitation>
). It also has a wide adventive distribution in southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[632,735,722,748]" name="Australia" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Australia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[786,893,722,748]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ponder, W. F." box="[906,1050,722,748]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="271 - 285" refId="ref67195" refString="Ponder, W. F. (1988) Potamopyrgus antipodarum - a molluscan colonizer of Europe and Australia. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 54 (3), 271 - 285. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / mollus / 54.3.271" type="journal article" year="1988">Ponder 1988</bibRefCitation>
) and Europe (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Welter-Schultes, F. W." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref70239" refString="Welter-Schultes, F. W. (2012) European Non-Marine Molluscs, a Guide for Species Identification: Bestimmungsbuch fur europaische Land-und Susswassermollusken. Planet Poster Editions, Gottingen, 760 pp." type="book" year="2012">Welter-Schultes 2012: 40</bibRefCitation>
), and is adventive also in North America (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Richards, D. C. &amp; Cazier, L. D. &amp; Lester, G. T." box="[768,992,758,784]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="375 - 380" refId="ref68080" refString="Richards, D. C., Cazier, L. D. &amp; Lester, G. T. (2001) Spatial distribution of three snail species, including the invader Potamopyrgus antipodarum, in a fresh-water spring. Western North American Naturalist, 61, 375 - 380." type="journal article" year="2001">
Richards 
<emphasis box="[873,921,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 2001
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Alonso, A. &amp; Castro-Diez, P." box="[1000,1313,758,784]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="107 - 116" refId="ref56885" refString="Alonso, A. &amp; Castro-Diez, P. (2008) What explains the invading success of the aquatic mud snail Potamopyrgus antipodarum (Hydrobiidae, Mollusca)? Hydrobiologia, 614 (1), 107 - 116. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10750 - 008 - 9529 - 3" type="journal article" year="2008">Alonso &amp; Castro-Diez 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[1372,1436,758,784]" name="Japan" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Shimada &amp; Urabe 2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,325,892]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,428,829,856]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Current taxonomy.</emphasis>
A subjective junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray, 1843)" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[800,1253,830,857]" class="Gastropoda" family="Tateidae" genus="Potamopygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="antipodarum">
<emphasis box="[800,1105,830,856]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Potamopygus antipodarum</emphasis>
(Gray, 1843)
</taxonomicName>
— 
<bibRefCitation author="Finlay, H. J." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="480 - 494" refId="ref60314" refString="Finlay, H. J. (1924) New Zealand Tertiary rissoids. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, 55, 480 - 494." type="journal article" year="1924">Finlay (1924: 491</bibRefCitation>
, 493), 
<bibRefCitation author="Marshall, B. A." box="[273,500,866,892]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref65698" refString="Marshall, B. A. (1996) Molluscan name-bearing types in the Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa. Tuhinga: Records of the Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, 9, 1 - 85." type="journal article" year="1996">Marshall (1996: 20)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
